335
00:35:16,108 --> 00:35:23,273
Please explain your position on whether using free cash to cover operating expenses is a fiscally sound policy and why.

336
00:35:25,083 --> 00:35:26,003
This is a very good question.

337
00:35:26,744 --> 00:35:36,129
So for those who don't know, free cash might sound like something wonderful and magical, but essentially it's over-budgeted money that the city over-budgets in a given year.

338
00:35:36,609 --> 00:35:46,214
And with the debate over whether or not we should pass our Proposition 2.5 overrides that we had just about a year ago, there was a lot of discussion about free cash and its viability.

339
00:35:46,894 --> 00:35:51,777
So the important thing to know about free cash is it's a limited amount of money and

340
00:35:52,477 --> 00:35:55,579
If we spend too much of it too quickly, it affects our city's bond rating.

341
00:35:55,639 --> 00:36:00,141
So we want to be intelligent about it, and typically it's only used for one-time expenditures.

342
00:36:00,902 --> 00:36:07,986
That said, though, my position with the overrides was that free cash could have been used smarter to meet our spending needs and avoid

343
00:36:08,646 --> 00:36:15,111
having to essentially hike taxes and put a significant burden on residents to meet our spending needs.

344
00:36:15,691 --> 00:36:19,374
So I think we can use free cash much more intelligently.

345
00:36:19,714 --> 00:36:21,736
That's going to be my position going forward.

346
00:36:22,176 --> 00:36:27,540
We can use it to meet our spending needs while also not raising concerns about our city's credit.

347
00:36:28,520 --> 00:36:29,641
So, free cash is out there.

348
00:36:29,821 --> 00:36:30,521
It is an option.

349
00:36:31,302 --> 00:36:43,168
And really, you know, my position with any sort of, you know, need for tax hikes in the future has been, you know, we should really, really look at every other alternative before we put that burden on residents.

350
00:36:43,188 --> 00:36:44,068
And they're struggling.

351
00:36:44,128 --> 00:36:50,131
There's a huge cost of living crisis out there and taxes are going up and rents are going up and people are really having a hard time.

352
00:36:50,612 --> 00:36:54,174
So, let's look at every other option before we put that burden on residents.

353
00:36:54,694 --> 00:36:54,954
Thank you.

